We had a detailed thread on this topic here on MLM several years ago
IIRC, so if you look for archived posts in your favorite search engine
you may get quite a bit of  opinion on the subject.   IIRC the main
upshot of those discussions was that the actual medical records, i.e.
the physical paper and/or hard drives etc. they are printed on and the
data that is in them, is the property of the medical provider who made
the records, but that HIPAA gives you the patient certain rights as to
the conditions under which the information in those records can be
shared with other people.

So, no, I don't think you have any right to actually destroy and/or
modify the original records and any modification or addition that the
provider does permit you to make will become part of the record along
with, but not in place of,  the original, allegedly "inappropriate"
record.

I have a hard time pinning down just what you are talking about as
"inappropriate"; do you mean medically incorrect (a misdiagnosis), or
do you mean the records include matters that you feel are medically
irrelevant and embarrassing/harmful (talking about a mental health
issue or an abortion or a drug habit or STDs in a simple whiplash case,
e.g.).

If it's the latter, I'm not surprised if it's the OTHER GUY's insurance
company you're talking about, since they routinely hire "hired gun"
doctors to examine the claimant and tell the jury that there's really
nothing wrong with her, that she's making it up for "secondary gain"
(i.e. to help her win more money in the lawsuit), that she's crazy in
the head, or blurting out other irrelevant but embarrassing facts about
your medical history that have nothing to do with your injuries from
the accident but which are brought up simply to make the jury less
likely to award in your favor, or to award as large an amount, as they
would have if the scurrilous facts had not been brought out.

Keep in mind that these "defense medical examiners" are NOT acting as
_your_ treating doctor when they do this, so they are not bound by
doctor-patient confidentiality (if your state even recognizes such a
thing) and they are being paid by the other guy's insurance company in
your accident case, expressly to SCREW you (ruin your case, that is).
They routinely write reports that include all kinds of heinous lies and
misinformation and share that info with the other guy's insurance
company and, if it comes to trial, with the jury, unless your own
attorney is diligent in filing motions to keep such irrelevant and
prejudicial stuff _out_ of the hearing of the jury (and even then, the
defense will finagle to let some of it get into evidence one way or
another).   If it's a defense medical exam and report you're talking
about, YES you may have rights to have such reports sealed and not be
used except by further court order (which a court, unfortunately, IS
likely to permit, if you get involved in _another_ accident case and
claim personal bodily injury).

You probably don't want to post details here out of privacy concerns,
of course, but if this really matters to you, you should consult an
actual, live lawyer locally who can hear all your facts in confidence,
keep your secrets for you, but can still advise you on how best to
proceed.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I'm also concerned because these records could
&gt; potentially impact the care I'll receive if I am hospitalized again.
">

No sensible doctor will want to treat you these days without checking
your relevant prior medical history first.   If this stuff you're
complaining about is truly irrelevant (your lawyer can advise you if it
is or not), you simply don't have to tell the new doctor about it when
he asks for your relevant medical history.   If it is something the
other side's insurance company will have access to in the event of a
later accident, however, your lawyer for the second accident BETTER
know about it, which means you will have to tell HIM and follow his
advice on who else you should tell.

Keep in mind that the insurance companies all share access to a massive
database called simply the "insurance index" and will routinely do an
"index search" on EVERY new claimant to find out all they can about ANY
prior claims you have ever made with ANY insurance co.   So, that
information IS out there, and there may not be anything you can do
about getting it sealed and hidden even if you DID have a legal right
to do so; at least, to the extent you may be a plaintiff or claimant in
a case arising from a later accident.   For personal injury claimants,
EVERYTHING in your past medical history is legally "relevant" at least
for "discovery" purposes, meaning the other side has a right to find
out about them even if it may not be "admissible" into evidence at
trial, so long as their request to obtain such information before trial
is "reasonably calculated" to _possibly_ lead to the discovery of
admissible evidence.   The pre-trial discovery rules, once a case is in
suit, are pretty broad and liberal about what they allow an
information-seeking opponent to find out about.

