&gt; Once again, if someone else is fully liable for my medical expenses, I
&gt; don't think I need to prove anything other than the amount of those
&gt; expenses in order to win a lawsuit to have him pay them.
">

First of all, a finding that someone is "fully liable" for your medical
expenses is a complex conclusion after all the evidence is in, not a
simple prior given that is known before you go to trial.  "Full
liability" means not only that the defendant's conduct was found to be
negligent (and also that you were _not_ found to be in any way
negligent, in most states using the comparative negligence rule), it
also means that the defendant's negligence was proven to be the legally
responsible (i.e. "proximate") cause of the specific injury you claim.

If someone runs a red light and T-bones your car, but you then claim
that the crash caused you to suffer, say, lung cancer, the insurer (and
juries) may be a bit skeptical and want to know about your past medical
history to try to refute that claim.  They'd want to know, for
instance, if you were a smoker, and if you ever worked with asbestos,
and if you ever worked around chemicals, and if you had a history of
emphysema or bronchitis, etc.  A claim that the crash caused you a
broken arm is a lot less likely to need corroborating proof of
causation, since it is fairly obvious that you were not already driving
along with bones sticking out of your arm and that the doctors put a
cast on you at the ER.   In the more common kinds of "soft-tissue-only"
injury claims, however, insurers and defense lawyers almost always do
challenge claims that their crash caused your injury, since it is quite
possible you were already experiencing aches and pains from some prior
incident before you got into the crash involving their insured driver.
They want to look for evidence to support a defense argument that it
was this prior condition, not the "light love tap" you received in the
crash at issue, that (at least in part) is responsible for your present
complaints and symptoms.   Often the defense will hire a medical expert
to examine you, review your prior records, and testify at trial to
support such arguments.

You're right IF what you mean is, that's all you have to prove (along
with some evidence of causation, if causation is not obvious from the
circumstances) in order to put on a prima facie tort case of damages in
a personal injury case.  But all that does is get you past a motion to
dismiss filed before the other side even has to put on any evidence.

That is not the same thing as saying you don't have to share your prior
medical records with the other side.   The defense is allowed to put on
a case too, and often, especially in cases of clear liability for the
crash itself, the defense effort focuses on _their_ medical experts'
claims (far fetched or otherwise) that it was not the crash that caused
the injury you are claiming, but rather some prior medical condition of
the victim for which the tortfeasor is not legally responsible.   That
argument often resonates with juries, unfortunately, even when it is
smoke and mirrors, and so as a practical matter, the plaintiff who
actually wants to WIN must do far more than the bare minimum required
to make a prima facie case.

So, before trial, the full range of plaintiff's prior medical history
is legally discoverable, subject only to the discretion of the court if
the plaintiff can convince the court to enter a protective order that
the particular material being sought is too remotely related to the
condition complained of to be of any possible relevance at trial and
thus is not "reasonably calculated to lead to discovery of admissible
evidence".

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; If his
&gt; insurance company won't defend or reimburse him unless I cooperate,
&gt; that's not my problem.
">

The insurer's refusal to pay (denial of your claim) in such a
circumstance just means they aren't willing to buy the pig in a poke
you are offering them.  If you want voluntary compensation paid before
filing suit, you still have to come up with the kind of evidence the
defense would like to see and would be legally entitled to ask for in
discovery after filing suit but before trial.  It is not an unfair
claim practice for them to do so; to the contrary, they have a duty to
their shareholders not to throw money away willy-nilly on potentially
frivolous claims where the claimant is not willing to provide
supporting evidence to prove the injury was not due to a prior medical
condition.  So it is very much your problem.

This is very different from an insurer's refusal to defend or to
reimburse their insured after you go all the way to trial and win a
verdict, and despite your use of those words I don't think that is what
you really had in mind.  Denial of a plaintiff's claim on factual
grounds relating to your particular claim is _not_ the same thing as
denial of any coverage at all for the insured defendant even if you
win.  A plaintiff claimant's refusal to cooperate provides no grounds
for a denial of _coverage_ since that would put control of whether or
not the defendant's insurance actually gave him any financial
protection in the hands of his opponent (you the plaintiff), an absurd
result.

But if you have forced the process to move to suit because you failed
to provide evidence of your prior medical history to defendant's
insurer voluntarily before suit, and if you likewise refuse to
cooperate in discovery with defendant's attorney after suit is filed,
chances are you will never get to the trial stage at all, since your
case is subject to being dismissed on the defense's motion as a
sanction for failure to provide discovery.

And if you do get to trial, you are frankly less than likely to
convince a jury to actually award you money, if the defense does raise
a medical causation issue and you choose not to actively refute it.
Doing so properly would require you to discuss your prior medical
history with the jury to show why you (and your medical expert
witnesses) claim that your history is NOT relevant to the proffered
lack-of-causation defense.   Either way, you have a choice: produce the
information, or lose the chance to get compensation for that part of
your claim even if the defendant's liability for the crash itself is
otherwise clear.

