Seth, you're missing the point that Stuart, more consisely than I, made
yesterday: how does the defendant's insurer, and then, the judge and/or
jury, determine which of your claimed expenses were actually due to the
injury caused by the accident?   This is called the "causation" issue.
None of those deciders is going to just take your word for it, unless,
as in your example below (and in my post yesterday), the causation is
clear and obvious, as with a broken bone.  For almost any other type of
claimed injury, they are going to want to look at your past medical
history, and the insurer's idea of what is relevant may be a lot
broader than yours.   Your remedy for that dispute is to seek a
protective order from the judge after your case is in suit if the other
side in fact requests production in discovery of materials you feel are
not sufficiently related to the issues in the suit to warrant
disclosure.   Just hiding those facts in the face of a facially
legitimate discovery request, in hopes the other side won't find out
about them, is a Very  Bad Idea since as several others have stated,
the other side may already know about them and your failure of
discovery could get your injury case dismissed or severely limited in
what the judge will allow you to claim.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; More detail of the hypothetical: I'm sitting in my own living room,
&gt; reading a book.  A car crashes through my wall and hits me, breaking
&gt; my legs.  I get medical treatment for the broken legs.
">

Causation for a cleanly broken bone from a substantial impact trauma is
pretty obvious.   How about if it was only a hairline fracture, and you
indeed had that history of college football?   Wouldn't the defense be
entitled to look at your old leg injury records to see if there is
anything in them supporting the possibility of an undiagnosed hairline
fracture earlier?   And in soft tissue, sprain-strain injuries, where
sometimes the only evidence of injury is the victim's complaints of
pain and the fact of the impact, it is quite possible that some of the
pain claimed could be either faked, or due to a pre-existing condition.
Defendants are allowed to find that out too.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I claim that the driver is fully responsible for the costs of the
&gt; medical treatment for my broken legs.  He can get records of that
&gt; treatment, copies of the x-rays of my legs, etc.  I don't see any
&gt; reason he should be able to get medical records of my shoulder surgery
&gt; from 5 years ago, or my childhood measles, or anything else not
&gt; related to the treatment he's responsible for paying for.
">

If they do ask for that stuff, you ask the judge for a protective
order, which he will either grant or not.   There is no hard and fast
rule; it is all very fact-specific to each case.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I shouldn't even have to provide records from my knee problems in
&gt; college, even though my current medical costs might be higher than
&gt; someone else's (if he didn't have similar knee problems) would be; the
&gt; driver takes his victim (me) as he finds him,
">

That is a true statement of the legal maxim, but the issue is, does it
apply to your case?   It is also true that, in the event he injures
someone like you with a pre-existing medical condition, the defendant
is only responsible for the ADDITIONAL pain and disability that he
caused over and above whatever you were still experiencing from your
earlier injury.   You claim you had zero residual pain and disability
from your football injuries?   Again, defense is not likely to take
that proffer at face value, and they are fully entitled by law to
inquire further, to see whether you are lying or exaggerating.   You
seem to be quite miffed that the other side in a lawsuit is not
required by law to believe everything you say without even a chance to
find possible cross-examination material.   In that case they might as
well not even show up for trial, and the judge can just award you
"fair" compensation based on your own testimony without the other side
ever having a chance to present contrary evidence.   I know you know
that is not how our adversary system works.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; and if he didn't want to
&gt; pay for treatment of someone with knee problems, he should have hit
&gt; someone else.
">

Although (at the end of a hard fought trial, in which your own advocate
will have to overcome the rocks thrown at your case by the defense
advocate) you _may_ wind up with the guy that hit you having to pay for
every bit of your claimed medical expense, plus an additional award for
your pain and suffering, you are putting the cart before the horse if
you say the defense is not even allowed to inquire into the possibility
of refuting these claims before trial.   That is what discovery is all
about.   After they look thru your prior meds and agree with you that
your college knee injury had nothing to do with the current symptoms,
they will probably settle, as happens more often than not.   But not
until you give them what they need to make sure they are not paying for
a false or exaggerated claim.

